<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1>What to Know If Your Child Has a Fracture of the Growth Plate</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#growth-plate">Growth plate</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#fracture">Fracture</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#symptoms">Symptoms</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#types">Types</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#causes">Causes</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#diagnosis">Diagnosis</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#treatment">Treatment</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#risk-factors">Risk factors</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#complications">Complications</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#outlook">Outlook</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#fa-qs">FAQs</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture-of-growth-plate#bottom-line">Bottom line</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Growth plate fractures are injuries to the soft connective tissue in the ends of long bones of children and teens. This soft tissue makes it possible for bones to grow as children age. It’s also weaker than other bone material and more susceptible to injury.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A growth plate fracture happens when an accident or overuse causes a break in the growth plate tissue. Without treatment, growth plate fractures can affect future bone growth. However, as long as treatment is prompt, many kids can recover from a growth plate fracture without any complications.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What is a growth plate?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A growth plate is a section of tissue near the end of the body’s long bones. Long bones are any bones that are longer than they are wide. They include bones in the arms, legs, and fingers. Growth plates are at either end of many long bones.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Throughout a person’s childhood and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/parenting/stages-of-puberty">teenage years</a>, growth plates are soft and allow bone growth. Growth plate tissue hardens into solid bone once a child finishes growing.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://b0a6183f29417872d2603045b7cad69f.safeframe.googlesyndication.com/safeframe/1-0-38/html/container.html"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-embed"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
https://b0a6183f29417872d2603045b7cad69f.safeframe.googlesyndication.com/safeframe/1-0-38/html/container.html
</div></figure>
<!-- /wp:embed -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What is a growth plate fracture?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Growth plates are the softest parts of the skeleton for children and teens. The tissue can&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/fracture">fracture</a>&nbsp;due to injury or overuse. Since growth plates are softer than bones, even injuries that seem mild could cause growth plate fractures. Fractures can happen on any growth plate, but it’s most common for kids to fracture the growth plates on their:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>fingers</li><li>lower leg bones</li><li>outer forearm bones</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Will a growth plate fracture affect bone growth?</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Many growth plate fractures heal without wasting complications, but growth plate fractures can affect bone growth.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The severity and location of the injury and the age of the child play a major role in how likely it is that a fracture will affect bone growth. For instance, a fracture to the growth plates around the knee can cause more lasting complications than a fracture to the growth plates around the wrist.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>No matter the location of the fracture, prompt and appropriate treatment can help reduce the risk of complications.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What are the symptoms of growth plate fracture?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It’s important to schedule an appointment with a doctor if you suspect your child has a growth plate fracture. Symptoms can depend on the severity and location of the future but often include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>soreness around the injury</li><li>tenderness when touching the area</li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/joint-swelling">swelling</a>&nbsp;near a joint</li><li>difficulty moving, putting weight on the limb, and doing recreational activities</li><li>repeated complaints of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/leg-pain">pain</a></li><li>visible changes in arm or leg form</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:image -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/post.psychcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2022/05/Thumbnail-Image-732x549-copy.jpg?w=1155" alt="SUBSCRIBE NOW"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.healthline.com/health/inline?correlationId=573af5b8-1b36-4c19-b2a5-a9a14a55f54d"></a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
